```suggestion
```

This suggestion comes up from time to time, but it's inconsistent to make the function computable.  (Inconsistent in the sense that you can write a function which provably returns true, but evaluates to false in the VM.)  See this [example from Chris Hughes](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/113488-general/topic/quotients.20and.20products.20again/near/187614136):

```lean
import Mathlib.Data.Setoid.Basic

def exoticInstance : Decidable True :=
  -- ⊤ is the always true relation
  @Quot.recOnSubsingleton _ _ (fun _ => Decidable True) _
    (@Quotient.choice (@Quotient Bool ⊤) (fun _ => Bool) ⊤ id)
    (fun f => decidable_of_iff (f ⟦false⟧ = f ⟦true⟧)
      (iff_true_intro (congr_arg f (Quotient.sound trivial))))

-- VM disagrees with type theory:
example : @decide True exoticInstance = true  := .trans (by congr) decide_True
example : @decide True exoticInstance = false := by native_decide

#eval exoticInstance -- isFalse _
```
Should that not be called something like `Quotient.eval` instead?
